<DOC><DOCNO> AP890118-0251 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 0053EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-18 0499</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0521</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent inNovember and sales rose at the same pace, the government said in areport that analysts said bodes well for the nation's economy in thenew year.   The Commerce Department said Tuesday inventories held on shelvesand backlots rose to a seasonally adjusted $753.6 billion inNovember, while sales reached $503.8 billion.   The matching 0.4 percent gains kept the ratio of inventories tosales at 1.50, meaning it would take 1.5 months to exhaustinventories at the November sales pace.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn has raised hisstake in Texaco Inc. to 16.6 percent and confirmed he was preparingfor the possibility of a second fight for control of the oil giant.   Icahn also accused Texaco management Tuesday of breaking apromise to shareholders by devising a new anti-takeover defense toreplace one that expires April 7.   He said the new strategy was an attempt to ``preclude a bid forTexaco by me or by anyone else ...''</TEXT><DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Financier Kirk Kerkorian pumped $180million into MGM-UA Communications Co. and revealed the latest in aseries of intricate blueprints for selling part of the strugglingmovie company he controls.   MGM-UA announced Tuesday Kerkorian's Tracinda Corp. had bought 10million shares of newly issued preferred stock for $18 a share.   The company also announced it would try to sell United Artistspart of the conglomerate Kerkorian assembled a decade ago fromassets of UA and the old Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studios.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gulf andamp; Western Inc. tentatively has agreed to adeal that would give it an option to buy a majority interest in TVXBroadcast Group Inc., which owns nine independent televisionstations, the companies said.   Gulf andamp; Western would buy the TVX stake from an affiliate ofSalomon Brothers Inc., the securities firm that helped TVX financeits purchase of five television stations in April 1987.   No price was disclosed Tuesday for the latest deal, but analystssaid it apparently would give Gulf andamp; Western a relativelyinexpensive entry into broadcast television.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company, and threeother big banking companies reported sharply higher earnings forboth the fourth quarter of 1988 and the whole year.   Most of the banks, which included J.P. Morgan andamp; Co., SecurityPacific Corp. and Wells Fargo andamp; Co., said Tuesday they were helpedpartly by tighter cost controls and Brazil's resumption of interestpayments on foreign loans.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Latin American nations must negotiate debtreduction agreements with commercial bank creditors or face aworsening economic situation that could lead to the return ofmilitary dictatorships in the region, a panel of experts said.   The recommendation was made in a report Tuesday by theInter-American Dialogue, a grouping of 66 prominent citizens fromthe United States, Canada, Latin America and the Caribbean.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>